h Poland has not traditionally had a large Roma population, the author leads the reader through an eventful history of a people living on the margins of contemporary Europe. The historic documents illustrate a marked contrast to present stereotypes and popular media images and shows how the position of Roma/Gypsies shifted gradually from respected, wealthy and partly settled citizens of the early modern times, towards criminalized vagrants of the 18 th century. This is a careful interpretation and re-interpretation of documents pertaining to the Roma's past that will provide an enlightening historical perspective towards the re-evaluation and self-definition of the Romani people in contemporary Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aLithuania (Grand Duchy) - Ethnic relations - History. 0aRomanieszLithuania (Grand Duchy)xHistoryvSources. 0aRomanieszLithuania (Grand Duchy)xHistory. 0aRomanieszPolandxHistoryvSources. 0aRomanieszPolandxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / European Studies.2bisacsh  aEarly modern Europe, Ethnic relations, History, Lithuania, Poland, Roma studies, Romanies, Sources.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2016z978311078053640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963386109740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633861097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633861097/original  a978-3-11-078053-6  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK